  "opinion": "As a 41-year-old immigrant living in Kansas City, unemployed but with good mental health, I approach fake content on social media with a mix of caution and empathy, shaped by my life experiences and personality. I use social media only a few times weekly, which helps me avoid the constant barrage of misinformation that more frequent users might face. My hobbies like reading novels and photography have taught me to appreciate nuance and authenticity, making me naturally skeptical of sensational posts. Being an atheist, I rely on evidence and reason rather than faith, which pushes me to fact-check before sharing anything. With three children, I'm especially vigilant about protecting my family from harmful falsehoods, often discussing media literacy with them during our baking or painting sessions. My high agreeableness means I value harmony and avoid confrontations online, so I typically ignore fake content rather than engage in arguments, but I might gently correct close friends in private messages. However, my high neuroticism makes me prone to anxiety, so encountering fake news about topics like health or immigration can unsettle me, leading me to take breaks from social media to run or read, activities that ground me. I believe managing fake content starts with personal responsibility: verifying sources through reputable sites, limiting exposure by curating feeds to trusted accounts, and educating others, especially my kids, about critical thinking. Social media platforms should improve moderation, but as an individual, I focus on what I can control—my own reactions and sharing habits. Ultimately, dealing with fake content is about balancing skepticism with compassion, ensuring it doesn't erode trust in genuine connections, which I cherish as an immigrant building a new community in Kansas City.",
